## 1. Summary

MIZAN v1 built its ethical foundation on principles derived by a single line of scholarly interpretation. This document argues that is the weak point, and replaces it with principles that recur independently across many moral traditions. The reasoning is that a principle found in many separate sources, across thousands of years, is harder to corrupt than one that depends on any single chain of interpretation.

The output is a set of fifteen convergent principles, each traced to multiple traditions, plus a list of the specific gaps in v1 that these principles close.

**Verdict:** convergence across independent sources is the most reliable ethical signal available. No single misreading can erase a principle that exists in too many places at once.

