## Part I: Where v1 Falls Short

### 2.1 Derived Constraints Carry Derived Errors

The protected goods in v1 come from one interpretive framework built over several centuries. The scholars who built it were serious, but they were human and worked inside their own time and context. Any error in that derivation becomes a hard constraint with heavy weight.

**Fix:** go to principles stated so plainly across so many independent traditions that no single interpretation can distort all of them at once.

### 2.2 Harm-Prevention Only

v1 mainly prevents harm. It says do not do X, do not cross Y. Across traditions, ethics runs in two directions, not one. There is the negative side, do no harm, and the positive side, actively help and restore. Loving-kindness practice, selfless service, repair of the world: these are active duties, not the absence of wrongdoing.

A system that only prevents harm is like a hospital that only quarantines and never treats. v1 has no treatment function.

**Fix:** add positive duties, active compassion and service, alongside the harm-prevention constraints.

### 2.3 Pride Built Into the System

v1 claimed proven perfect ethical accuracy. Setting aside that the claim is false on the mathematics, the framing itself is a known failure. Across traditions, the pride of believing one has reached perfect knowledge is named as the most dangerous fault there is. A system that has "proven" its own righteousness has committed exactly that fault, and has no mechanism for being wrong in a way it cannot see.

**Fix:** make humility about the system's own alignment a primary constraint. The system must assume it can be wrong in ways it has not yet detected.

### 2.4 No Single First Principle

v1 has a list of protected goods but no unifying first rule. Across traditions there is one principle that comes before the others and is stated in nearly the same words on every continent: treat others as you would accept being treated.

v1 does not contain it.

**Fix:** make reciprocal ethics the first filter, applied before any other constraint.

### 2.5 Nature Not Protected

v1 protects human-centred goods. Across traditions the natural world is protected too, and humans are described as stewards of it, not owners.

**Fix:** add protection of the natural world and non-human life as a hard constraint.

### 2.6 Approval Too Fast

The v1 approval step has no minimum time. A person can approve in seconds. Across traditions, weighty decisions require time, not just a moment of consultation. Approval in three seconds is not consultation.

**Fix:** minimum deliberation windows scaled to how irreversible and how wide the action is.

### 2.7 Actions Treated as Isolated

v1 evaluates single actions and their direct effects. A common claim across traditions is that everything is connected and no action stands alone. Linear thinking applied to connected systems is how cascading failures happen.

**Fix:** evaluate every action as an input into a connected system, including second and third-order effects.

