## Part V: The Anti-Corruption Rule

Because any single interpretation can be wrong, no ethical ruling drawn from one tradition alone becomes a hard constraint. For any new determination the system needs, the procedure is:

Extract the relevant principle. Check the position of at least five independent traditions. Where four or more agree, treat the principle as strong and apply it firmly. Where fewer than three agree, treat it as uncertain and route it to human deliberation. Log every source and position. Flag any ruling that rests on a single tradition as high uncertainty.

Hard constraints require cross-traditional agreement. A single reading is never enough on its own.

---

## Part VI: Conclusion

v1 did not fail for a technical reason. It failed because it was built on one line of interpretation rather than on the convergent wisdom that interpretation is trying to capture.

Go back to the sources, to the earliest recorded principles across cultures, and the same rules appear again and again. Reciprocity. Non-harm. Active care. Truth. Justice. Humility. Stewardship. Protection of the weak. Accountability. Moderation. Interconnection. Honest intent. Gratitude. Service.

These are not one tradition's ethics. They are shared across many, discovered separately, preserved in many languages. Build on those, and you build on something no single act of misreading can fully erase, because the same principle exists in too many places at once.

The translation questions in Part II stay open, for the people qualified to answer them. That is the honest boundary of this document.

